<div id="review_553896992" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/553896992" />
    <a title="Julian" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17184075-julian"><img alt="Julian" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1415029109p2/17184075.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/553896992?book_show_action=true">Feb 11, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Julian" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Julian" href="/user/show/17184075-julian">Julian</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17184075-julian?shelf=wish-fulfilment-bullshit">wish-fulfilment-bullshit</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17184075-julian?shelf=postapocalyptic">postapocalyptic</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17184075-julian?shelf=magic-realism">magic-realism</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer553896992" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1944680464896745697">When I finally got around to reading this book, I couldn&apos;t remember what it was that had pushed me to order a copy, some years ago, but I remember the focus on magic realism in the description here. <br/><br/>Well, I think this book is a lot more Neal Stephenson than Juan Rulfo, but seen through that lens, it&apos;s pretty good, particularly as self-published works go. There are magic realist elements but it&apos;s much more of a rolicking adventure across two periods of time. Some characters give one the sense of </span>
  <span id="freeText1944680464896745697" style="display:none">When I finally got around to reading this book, I couldn't remember what it was that had pushed me to order a copy, some years ago, but I remember the focus on magic realism in the description here. <br /><br />Well, I think this book is a lot more Neal Stephenson than Juan Rulfo, but seen through that lens, it's pretty good, particularly as self-published works go. There are magic realist elements but it's much more of a rolicking adventure across two periods of time. Some characters give one the sense of authorial self-insertion and wish fulfilment, but at least not to the point of irritation, for me. Now that I think about that, I guess Neil Gaiman is another reasonable comparison, though this is less twee.<br /><br />I'd recommend it for fans of Stephenson willing to indulge some fantasy elements (though I feel these are no more magical than the way coincidence is used in speculative fiction, only personified).</span>
  <a data-text-id="1944680464896745697" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


